# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: session-types
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:session-types/behavioral-subtyping] Specifically, properties that clients can prove using the specification of an object's presumed type should hold even though the object is actually a member of a subtype of that type.
[src:session-types/behavioral-subtyping] For example, consider a type Stack and a type Queue, which both have a *put* method to add an element and a *get* method to remove one.
[src:session-types/behavioral-subtyping] Suppose the documentation associated with these types specifies that type Stack's methods shall behave as expected for stacks (i.e. they shall exhibit LIFO behavior), and that type Queue's methods shall behave as expected for queues (i.e. they shall exhibit FIFO behavior).
[src:session-types/behavioral-subtyping] Suppose, now, that type Stack was declared as a subclass of type Queue.
[src:session-types/behavioral-subtyping] Most programming language compilers ignore documentation and perform only the checks that are necessary to preserve type safety.
[src:session-types/behavioral-subtyping] Since, for each method of type Queue, type Stack provides a method with a matching name and signature, this check would succeed.
[src:session-types/behavioral-subtyping] However, clients accessing a Stack object through a reference of type Queue would, based on Queue's documentation, expect FIFO behavior but observe LIFO behavior, invalidating these clients' correctness proofs and potentially leading to incorrect behavior of the program as a whole.
[src:session-types/behavioral-subtyping] This example violates behavioral subtyping because type Stack is not a behavioral subtype of type Queue: it is not the case that the behavior described by the documentation of type Stack (i.e.
[src:session-types/behavioral-subtyping] LIFO behavior) complies with the documentation of type Queue (which requires FIFO behavior).
[src:session-types/behavioral-subtyping] Indeed, any object that satisfies the Stack or Queue specification also satisfies the Bag specification.
[src:session-types/behavioral-subtyping] It is important to stress that whether a type S is a behavioral subtype of a type T depends only on the *specification* (i.e. the *documentation*) of type T; the *implementation* of type T, if it has any, is completely irrelevant to this question.
[src:session-types/behavioral-subtyping] Indeed, type T need not even have an implementation; it might be a purely abstract class.
[src:session-types/behavioral-subtyping] As another case in point, type Stack above is a behavioral subtype of type Bag even if type Bag's *implementation* exhibits FIFO behavior: what matters is that type Bag's *specification* does not specify which element is removed by method *get*.
[src:session-types/behavioral-subtyping] This also means that behavioral subtyping can be discussed only with respect to a particular (behavioral) specification for each type involved and that if the types involved have no well-defined behavioral specification, behavioral subtyping cannot be discussed meaningfully.
[src:session-types/behavioral-subtyping] A type S is a behavioral subtype of a type T if each behavior allowed by the specification of S is also allowed by the specification of T.
[src:session-types/behavioral-subtyping] This requires, in particular, that for each method M of T, the specification of M in S is *stronger* than the one in T.
[src:session-types/behavioral-subtyping] A method specification given by a precondition Ps and a postcondition Qs is stronger than one given by a precondition Pt and a postcondition Qt (formally: (Ps, Qs) ⇒ (Pt, Qt)) if Ps is *weaker* than Pt (i.e.
[src:session-types/behavioral-subtyping] Pt implies Ps) and Qs is stronger than Qt (i.e.
[src:session-types/behavioral-subtyping] That is, strengthening a method specification can be done by strengthening the postcondition and by *weakening* the precondition.
[src:session-types/behavioral-subtyping] Indeed, a method specification is stronger if it imposes more specific constraints on the outputs for inputs that were already supported, or if it requires more inputs to be supported.
[src:session-types/behavioral-subtyping] For example, consider the (very weak) specification for a method that computes the absolute value of an argument *x*, that specifies a precondition 0 ≤ x and a postcondition 0 ≤ result.
[src:session-types/behavioral-subtyping] This specification says the method need not support negative values for *x*, and it need only ensure the result is nonnegative as well.
[src:session-types/behavioral-subtyping] Two possible ways to strengthen this specification are by strengthening the postcondition to state result = |x|, i.e. the result is equal to the absolute value of x, or by weakening the precondition to "true", i.e. all values for *x* should be supported.
[src:session-types/behavioral-subtyping] Of course, we can also combine both, into a specification that states that the result should equal the absolute value of *x*, for any value of *x*.
[src:session-types/behavioral-subtyping] Note, however, that it is possible to strengthen a specification ((Ps, Qs) ⇒ (Pt, Qt)) without strengthening the postcondition (Qs ⇏ Qt).
[src:session-types/behavioral-subtyping] Consider a specification for the absolute value method that specifies a precondition 0 ≤ x and a postcondition result = x.
[src:session-types/behavioral-subtyping] The specification that specifies a precondition "true" and a postcondition result = |x| strengthens this specification, even though the postcondition result = |x| does not strengthen (or weaken) the postcondition result = x.
[src:session-types/behavioral-subtyping] The necessary condition for a specification with precondition Ps and postcondition Qs to be stronger than a specification with precondition Pt and postcondition Qt is that Ps is weaker than Pt and "Qs or not Ps" is stronger than "Qt or not Pt".
[src:session-types/behavioral-subtyping] Indeed, "result = |x| or false" does strengthen "result = x or x < 0".
[src:session-types/behavioral-subtyping] Unfortunately, though, it has several issues.
[src:session-types/behavioral-subtyping] Secondly, it makes no mention of *specifications*, so it invites an incorrect reading where the *implementation* of type S is compared to the *implementation* of type T.
[src:session-types/behavioral-subtyping] This is problematic for several reasons, one being that it does not support the common case where T is abstract and has no implementation.
[src:session-types/behavioral-subtyping] Thirdly, and most subtly, in the context of object-oriented imperative programming it is difficult to define precisely what it means to universally or existentially quantify over objects of a given type, or to substitute one object for another.
[src:session-types/behavioral-subtyping] In the example above, we are not substituting a Stack object for a Bag object, we are simply using a Stack object as a Bag object.
[src:session-types/behavioral-subtyping] During the interview, she does not use substitution terminology to discuss the concepts.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] A **communication protocol** is a system of rules that allows two or more entities of a communications system to transmit information.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The protocol defines the rules, syntax, semantics, and synchronization of communication and possible error recovery methods.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Protocols may be implemented by hardware, software, or a combination of both.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Communicating systems use well-defined formats for exchanging various messages.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Each message has an exact meaning intended to elicit a response from a range of possible responses predetermined for that particular situation.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The specified behavior is typically independent of how it is to be implemented.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Communication protocols have to be agreed upon by the parties involved.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] To reach an agreement, a protocol may be developed into a technical standard.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] A programming language describes the same for computations, so there is a close analogy between protocols and programming languages: *protocols are to communication what programming languages are to computations*.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] An alternate formulation states that *protocols are to communication what algorithms are to computation*.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Multiple protocols often describe different aspects of a single communication.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] A group of protocols designed to work together is known as a protocol suite; when implemented in software, they are a protocol stack.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Some of the most well-known communication protocols are those related to the Internet, web, and email, which are developed and published by the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF), and World Wide Web Consortium.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Many wired and wireless protocols are also well known, such as Ethernet, Bluetooth, and of course mobile phone standards.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] These are mostly handled by the IEEE (Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers, e.g., Ethernet).
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] There is also the ITU-T, which handles telecommunications protocols & formats for the public switched telephone network (PSTN).
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] As the PSTN and Internet converge, many protocols are trending towards convergence.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The International Organization for Standardization (ISO) handles many other types.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] They published their work the following year.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] On the ARPANET, the starting point for host-to-host communication in 1969 was the 1822 protocol, written by Bob Kahn, which defined the transmission of messages to an IMP.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The Network Control Program (NCP) for the ARPANET, developed by Steve Crocker and other graduate students including Jon Postel, was first implemented in 1970.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The NCP interface allowed application software to connect across the ARPANET by implementing higher-level communication protocols, an early example of the *protocol layering* concept.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The CYCLADES network, designed by Louis Pouzin in the early 1970s, was the first to implement the end-to-end principle, and make the hosts responsible for the reliable delivery of data on a packet-switched network, rather than this being a service of the network itself.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] His team was the first to tackle the highly complex problem of providing user applications with a reliable virtual circuit service while using a best-effort service, an early contribution to what will be the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Bob Metcalfe and others at Xerox PARC outlined the idea of Ethernet and the PARC Universal Packet (PUP) for internetworking.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Research in the early 1970s by Bob Kahn and Vint Cerf led to the formulation of the Transmission Control Program (TCP).
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Its RFC 675 specification was written by Cerf with Yogen Dalal and Carl Sunshine in December 1974, still a monolithic design at this time.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The International Network Working Group agreed on a connectionless datagram standard, which was presented to the CCITT in 1975 but was not adopted by the CCITT nor by the ARPANET.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Separate international research, particularly the work of Rémi Després, contributed to the development of the X.25 standard, based on virtual circuits, which was adopted by the CCITT in 1976.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Computer manufacturers developed proprietary protocols such as IBM's Systems Network Architecture (SNA), Digital Equipment Corporation's DECnet and Xerox Network Systems.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] TCP software was redesigned as a modular protocol stack, referred to as *TCP/IP.* This was installed on SATNET in 1982 and on the ARPANET in January 1983.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The development of a complete Internet protocol suite by 1989, as outlined in RFC 1122 and RFC 1123, laid the foundation for the growth of TCP/IP as a comprehensive protocol suite as the core component of the emerging Internet.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] International work on a reference model for communication standards led to the OSI model, published in 1984.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] For a period in the late 1980s and early 1990s, engineers, organizations and nations became polarized over the issue of which standard, the OSI model or the Internet protocol suite, would result in the best and most robust computer networks.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The information exchanged between devices through a network or other media is governed by rules and conventions that can be set out in communication protocol specifications.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The nature of communication, the actual data exchanged and any state-dependent behaviors, is defined by these specifications.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] In digital computing systems, the rules can be expressed by algorithms and data structures.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Protocols are to communication what algorithms or programming languages are to computations.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Operating systems usually contain a set of cooperating processes that manipulate shared data to communicate with each other.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] This communication is governed by well-understood protocols, which can be embedded in the process code itself.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] In contrast, because there is no shared memory, communicating systems have to communicate with each other using a shared transmission medium.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Transmission is not necessarily reliable, and individual systems may use different hardware or operating systems.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] To implement a networking protocol, the protocol software modules are interfaced with a framework implemented on the machine's operating system.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] This framework implements the networking functionality of the operating system.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] When protocol algorithms are expressed in a portable programming language the protocol software may be made operating system independent.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The best-known frameworks are the TCP/IP model and the OSI model.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] This gave rise to the concept of layered protocols, which nowadays forms the basis of protocol design.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Systems typically do not use a single protocol to handle a transmission.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Instead, they use a set of cooperating protocols, sometimes called a protocol suite.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Some of the best-known protocol suites are TCP/IP, IPX/SPX, X.25, AX.25 and AppleTalk.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The protocols can be arranged based on functionality in groups; for instance, there is a group of transport protocols.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The functionalities are mapped onto the layers, each layer solving a distinct class of problems relating to, for instance: application-, transport-, internet- and network interface-functions.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] To transmit a message, a protocol has to be selected from each layer.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The selection of the next protocol is accomplished by extending the message with a protocol selector for each layer.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Communication protocols define the representation of messages exchanged between communicating systems.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Common approaches to message encoding use text or binary representations.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] A **text-based protocol** or **plain text protocol** represents its messages in human-readable format, often in plain text encoded in a machine-readable encoding such as ASCII or UTF-8, or in structured text-based formats such as Intel hex format, XML or JSON.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The immediate human readability stands in contrast with binary message representations, which have inherent benefits for use in a computer environment (such as ease of mechanical parsing and improved bandwidth utilization).
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Network applications have various methods of encapsulating data.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] One method very common with Internet protocols is a text-oriented message representation that transmits requests and responses as lines of ASCII text, terminated by a newline character (and usually a carriage return character).
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Examples of protocols that use plain, human-readable text for their commands are FTP (File Transfer Protocol), SMTP (Simple Mail Transfer Protocol), early versions of HTTP (Hypertext Transfer Protocol), and the finger protocol.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Text-based message representations are typically easier for humans to inspect and interpret, and are therefore suitable whenever human inspection of protocol contents is required, such as during debugging and during early protocol development design phases.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] A **binary protocol** uses a message representation that may utilize all values of a byte, as opposed to a text-based representation, which is limited to values corresponding to characters in a character encoding such as ASCII or UTF-8.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Binary message representations are intended to be processed by machines rather than read directly by humans.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Binary protocols have the advantage of terseness, which translates into speed of transmission and interpretation.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Binary message representations have been used in modern standards such as EbXML, HTTP/2, HTTP/3, and EDOC.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] An interface in UML may also be considered a binary protocol.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Getting the data across a network is only part of the problem for a protocol.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The data received has to be evaluated in the context of the progress of the conversation, so a protocol must include rules describing the context.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] These kinds of rules are said to express the *syntax* of the communication.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Other rules determine whether the data is meaningful for the context in which the exchange takes place.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] These kinds of rules are said to express the *semantics* of the communication.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Messages are sent and received on communicating systems to establish communication.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Protocols should therefore specify rules governing the transmission.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Digital message bitstrings are exchanged.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The bitstrings are divided in fields and each field carries information relevant to the protocol.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The actual message is carried in the payload.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The header area contains the fields relevant to the operation of the protocol.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] (MTU) are divided in pieces of appropriate size.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Addresses are used to identify both the sender and the intended receiver(s).
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The addresses are carried in the header area of the bitstrings, allowing the receivers to determine whether the bitstrings are of interest and should be processed or should be ignored.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Usually, some address values have special meanings.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] s address could be taken to mean an addressing of all stations on the network, so sending to this address would result in a broadcast on the local network.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Sometimes protocols need to map addresses of one scheme on addresses of another scheme.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] For instance, to translate a logical IP address specified by the application to an Ethernet MAC address.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] to the intended receiver(s) need to forward messages on behalf of the sender.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] On the Internet, the networks are connected using routers.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Error detection is necessary on networks where data corruption is possible.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] In a common approach, a CRC of the data area is added to the end of packets, making it possible for the receiver to detect differences caused by corruption.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The receiver rejects the packets on CRC differences and arranges somehow for retransmission.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Acknowledgments are sent from receivers back to their respective senders.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Packets may be lost on the network or be delayed in transit.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] To cope with this, under some protocols, a sender may expect an acknowledgment of correct reception from the receiver within a certain amount of time.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] , the sender may need to retransmit the information.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] In case of a permanently broken link, the retransmission has no effect, so the number of retransmissions is limited.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Exceeding the retry limit is considered an error.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] where two parties respectively simultaneously transmit or wish to transmit.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] If long bitstrings are divided into pieces and then sent on the network individually, the pieces may get lost or delayed or, on some types of networks, take different routes to their destination.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] As a result, pieces may arrive out of sequence.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Retransmissions can result in duplicate pieces.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] By marking the pieces with sequence information at the sender, the receiver can determine what was lost or duplicated, ask for necessary retransmissions and reassemble the original message.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Flow control is needed when the sender transmits faster than the receiver or intermediate network equipment can process the transmissions.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Flow control can be implemented by messaging from receiver to sender.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Communicating processes or state machines employ queues (or "buffers"), usually FIFO queues, to deal with the messages in the order sent, and may sometimes have multiple queues with different prioritization.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Systems engineering principles have been applied to create a set of common network protocol design principles.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The design of complex protocols often involves decomposition into simpler, cooperating protocols.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Such a set of cooperating protocols is sometimes called a protocol family or a protocol suite, within a conceptual framework.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Communicating systems operate concurrently.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] An important aspect of concurrent programming is the synchronization of software for receiving and transmitting messages of communication in proper sequencing.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Concurrent programming has traditionally been a topic in operating systems theory texts.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Formal verification seems indispensable because concurrent programs are notorious for the hidden and sophisticated bugs they contain.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] A mathematical approach to the study of concurrency and communication is referred to as communicating sequential processes (CSP).
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Concurrency can also be modeled using finite-state machines, such as Mealy and Moore machines.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Mealy and Moore machines are in use as design tools in digital electronics systems encountered in the form of hardware used in telecommunication or electronic devices in general.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The literature presents numerous analogies between computer communication and programming.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] In analogy, a transfer mechanism of a protocol is comparable to a central processing unit (CPU).
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The framework introduces rules that allow the programmer to design cooperating protocols independently of one another.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] In modern protocol design, protocols are layered to form a protocol stack.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Layering is a design principle that divides the protocol design task into smaller steps, each of which accomplishes a specific part, interacting with the other parts of the protocol only in a small number of well-defined ways.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Layering allows the parts of a protocol to be designed and tested without a combinatorial explosion of cases, keeping each design relatively simple.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The communication protocols in use on the Internet are designed to function in diverse and complex settings.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Internet protocols are designed for simplicity and modularity and fit into a coarse hierarchy of functional layers defined in the Internet Protocol Suite.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The first two cooperating protocols, the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) and the Internet Protocol (IP) resulted from the decomposition of the original Transmission Control Program, a monolithic communication protocol, into this layered communication suite.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The OSI model was developed internationally based on experience with networks that predated the Internet as a reference model for general communication with much stricter rules of protocol interaction and rigorous layering.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Typically, application software is built upon a robust data transport layer.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Underlying this transport layer is a datagram delivery and routing mechanism that is typically connectionless in the Internet.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Packet relaying across networks happens over another layer that involves only network link technologies, which are often specific to certain physical layer technologies, such as Ethernet.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Layering provides opportunities to exchange technologies when needed, for example, protocols are often stacked in a tunneling arrangement to accommodate the connection of dissimilar networks.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] For example, IP may be tunneled across an Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM) network.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Protocol layering forms the basis of protocol design.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] It allows the decomposition of single, complex protocols into simpler, cooperating protocols.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The protocol layers each solve a distinct class of communication problems.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Together, the layers make up a layering scheme or model.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Computations deal with algorithms and data; Communication involves protocols and messages; So the analog of a data flow diagram is some kind of message flow diagram.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] To visualize protocol layering and protocol suites, a diagram of the message flows in and between two systems, A and B, is shown in figure 3.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The systems, A and B, both make use of the same protocol suite.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The vertical flows (and protocols) are in-system and the horizontal message flows (and protocols) are between systems.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The message flows are governed by rules, and data formats specified by protocols.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The blue lines mark the boundaries of the (horizontal) protocol layers.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The software supporting protocols has a layered organization, and its relationship with protocol layering is shown in figure 5.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] To send a message on system A, the top-layer software module interacts with the module directly below it and hands over the message to be encapsulated.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The lower module fills in the header data in accordance with the protocol it implements and interacts with the bottom module, which sends the message over the communications channel to the bottom module of system B.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] On the receiving system B the reverse happens, so ultimately the message gets delivered in its original form to the top module of system B.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Program translation is divided into subproblems.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] As a result, the translation software is layered as well, allowing the software layers to be designed independently.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The same approach can be seen in the TCP/IP layering.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The modules below the application layer are generally considered part of the operating system.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Passing data between these modules is much less expensive than passing data between an application program and the transport layer.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The boundary between the application layer and the transport layer is called the operating system boundary.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Strictly adhering to a layered model, a practice known as strict layering, is not always the best approach to networking.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Strict layering can have a negative impact on the performance of an implementation.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Commonly recurring problems in the design and implementation of communication protocols can be addressed by software design patterns.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Popular formal methods of describing communication syntax are Abstract Syntax Notation One (an ISO standard) and augmented Backus–Naur form (an IETF standard).
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] For communication to occur, protocols have to be selected.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The rules can be expressed by algorithms and data structures.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Hardware and operating system independence is enhanced by expressing the algorithms in a portable programming language.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Source independence of the specification provides wider interoperability.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Protocol standards are commonly created by obtaining the approval or support of a standards organization, which initiates the standardization process.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The members of the standards organization agree to adhere to the work result on a voluntary basis.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Often, the members are in control of large market shares relevant to the protocol, and in many cases, standards are enforced by law or the government because they are thought to serve an important public interest, so getting approval can be very important for the protocol.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The need for protocol standards can be shown by looking at what happened to the Binary Synchronous Communications (BSC) protocol invented by IBM.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] BSC is an early link-level protocol used to connect two separate nodes.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] It was originally not intended to be used in a multinode network, but doing so revealed several deficiencies of the protocol.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] In the absence of standardization, manufacturers and organizations felt free to enhance the protocol, creating incompatible versions on their networks.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] In some cases, this was deliberately done to discourage users from using equipment from other manufacturers.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] There are more than 50 variants of the original bi-sync protocol.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] One can assume that a standard would have prevented at least some of this from happening.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] In some cases, protocols gain market dominance without going through a standardization process.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Such protocols are referred to as *de facto standards*.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] De facto standards are common in emerging markets, niche markets, or markets that are monopolized (or oligopolized).
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] They can hold a market in a very negative grip, especially when used to scare away competition.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] From a historical perspective, standardization should be seen as a measure to counteract the ill effects of de facto standards.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Positive exceptions exist; a de facto standard operating system like Linux does not have this negative grip on its market because the sources are published and maintained in an open way, thus inviting competition.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Some of the standards organizations of relevance for communication protocols are the International Organization for Standardization (ISO), the International Telecommunication Union (ITU), the Institute of Electrical and Electronics Engineers (IEEE), and the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF).
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The IETF maintains the protocols in use on the Internet.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The IEEE controls many software and hardware protocols in the electronics industry for commercial and consumer devices.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The ITU is an umbrella organization of telecommunication engineers designing the public switched telephone network (PSTN), as well as many radio communication systems.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] For marine electronics, the NMEA standards are used.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The World Wide Web Consortium (W3C) produces protocols and standards for Web technologies.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] International standards organizations are supposed to be more impartial than local organizations with a national or commercial self-interest to consider.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Standards organizations also do research and development for standards of the future.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] In practice, the standards organizations mentioned cooperate closely with each other.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Multiple standards bodies may be involved in the development of a protocol.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] In the ISO, the standardization process starts off with the commissioning of a sub-committee workgroup.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The workgroup issues working drafts and discussion documents to interested parties (including other standards bodies) in order to provoke discussion and comments.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] This will generate a lot of questions, much discussion and usually some disagreement.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] These comments are taken into account, and a *draft proposal* is produced by the working group.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] After feedback, modification, and compromise, the proposal reaches the status of a *draft international standard*, and ultimately an *international standard*.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] International standards are reissued periodically to address deficiencies and reflect changing views on the subject.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] A lesson learned from ARPANET, the predecessor of the Internet, was that protocols need a framework to operate.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] It is therefore important to develop a general-purpose, future-proof framework suitable for *structured protocols* (such as layered protocols) and their standardization.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] This would prevent protocol standards with overlapping functionality and would allow a clear definition of the responsibilities of a protocol at the different levels (layers).
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] This gave rise to the Open Systems Interconnection model (OSI model), which is used as a framework for the design of standard protocols and services conforming to the various layer specifications.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] In the OSI model, communicating systems are assumed to be connected by an underlying physical medium providing a basic transmission mechanism.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Each layer provides service to the layer above it using the services of the layer immediately below it.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The top layer provides services to the application process.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The layers communicate with each other by means of an interface, called a *service access point*.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Corresponding layers at each system are called *peer entities*.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] To communicate, two peer entities at a given layer use a protocol specific to that layer, which is implemented by using services of the layer below.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] For each layer, there are two types of standards: protocol standards defining how peer entities at a given layer communicate, and service standards defining how a given layer communicates with the layer above it.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] In contrast to the TCP/IP layering scheme, which assumes a connectionless network, RM/OSI assumed a connection-oriented network.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Connection-oriented networks are more suitable for wide area networks and connectionless networks are more suitable for local area networks.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Connection-oriented communication requires some form of session and (virtual) circuits, hence the (in the TCP/IP model lacking) session layer.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The constituent members of ISO were mostly concerned with wide area networks, so the development of RM/OSI concentrated on connection-oriented networks and connectionless networks were first mentioned in an addendum to RM/OSI and later incorporated into an update to RM/OSI.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] At the time, the IETF had to cope with this and the fact that the Internet needed protocols that simply were not there.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] As a result, the IETF developed its own standardization process based on "rough consensus and running code".
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The standardization process is described by RFC 2026.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Nowadays, the IETF has become a standards organization for the protocols in use on the Internet.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] RM/OSI has extended its model to include connectionless services, and because of this, both TCP and IP could be developed into international standards.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The *wire image* of a protocol is the information that a non-participant observer is able to glean from observing the protocol messages, including both information explicitly given meaning by the protocol, but also inferences made by the observer.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Unencrypted protocol metadata is one source making up the wire image, and side-channels including packet timing also contribute.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Different observers with different vantages may see different wire images.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The wire image is relevant to end-user privacy and the extensibility of the protocol.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] If some portion of the wire image is not cryptographically authenticated, it is subject to modification by intermediate parties (i.e., middleboxes), which can influence protocol operation.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Even if authenticated, if a portion is not encrypted, it will form part of the wire image, and intermediate parties may intervene depending on its content (e.g., dropping packets with particular flags).
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Signals deliberately intended for intermediary consumption may be left authenticated but unencrypted.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The wire image can be deliberately engineered, encrypting parts that intermediaries should not be able to observe and providing signals for what they should be able to.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] If provided signals are decoupled from the protocol's operation, they may become untrustworthy.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Benign network management and research are affected by metadata encryption; protocol designers must balance observability for operability and research against ossification resistance and end-user privacy.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Engineering the wire image and controlling what signals are provided to network elements was a "developing field" in 2023, according to the IAB.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Protocol ossification is the loss of flexibility, extensibility and evolvability of network protocols.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] This is largely due to middleboxes that are sensitive to the wire image of the protocol, and which can interrupt or interfere with messages that are valid but which the middlebox does not correctly recognize.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] This is a violation of the end-to-end principle.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Secondary causes include inflexibility in endpoint implementations of protocols.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Because of ossification, the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) and User Datagram Protocol (UDP) are the only practical choices for transport protocols on the Internet, and TCP itself has significantly ossified, making extension or modification of the protocol difficult.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Recommended methods of preventing ossification include encrypting protocol metadata, and ensuring that extension points are exercised and wire image variability is exhibited as fully as possible; remedying existing ossification requires coordination across protocol participants.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] QUIC is the first IETF transport protocol to have been designed with deliberate anti-ossification properties.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Classification schemes for protocols usually focus on the domain of use and function.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] As an example of domain of use, connection-oriented protocols and connectionless protocols are used on connection-oriented networks and connectionless networks, respectively.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] An example of function is a tunneling protocol, which is used to encapsulate packets in a high-level protocol so that the packets can be passed across a transport system using the high-level protocol.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] A *layering scheme* combines both function and domain of use.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The dominant layering schemes are the ones developed by the IETF and by ISO.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Despite the fact that the underlying assumptions of the layering schemes are different enough to warrant distinguishing the two, it is a common practice to compare the two by relating common protocols to the layers of the two schemes.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The layering scheme from the IETF is called *Internet layering* or *TCP/IP layering*.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] The layering scheme from ISO is called *the OSI model* or *ISO layering*.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] In networking equipment configuration, a term-of-art distinction is often drawn: The term *protocol* strictly refers to the transport layer, and the term *service* refers to protocols utilizing a *protocol* for transport.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] In the common case of TCP and UDP, services are distinguished by port numbers.
[src:session-types/communication-protocol] Conformance to these port numbers is voluntary, so in content inspection systems, the term *service* strictly refers to port numbers, and the term *application* is often used to refer to protocols identified through inspection signatures.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] In mathematics, a **duality** translates concepts, theorems or mathematical structures into other concepts, theorems or structures in a one-to-one fashion, often (but not always) by means of an involution operation: if the dual of A is B, then the dual of B is A.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] In other cases the dual of the dual – the double dual or bidual – is not necessarily identical to the original (also called *primal*).
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] Such involutions sometimes have fixed points, so that the dual of A is A itself.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] For example, Desargues' theorem is **self-dual** in this sense under the *standard duality in projective geometry*.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] In mathematical contexts, *duality* has numerous meanings.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] It has been described as "a very pervasive and important concept in (modern) mathematics" and "an important general theme that has manifestations in almost every area of mathematics".
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] Many mathematical dualities between objects of two types correspond to pairings, bilinear functions from an object of one type and another object of the second type to some family of scalars.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] From a category theory viewpoint, duality can also be seen as a functor, at least in the realm of vector spaces.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] This functor assigns to each space its dual space, and the pullback construction assigns to each arrow *f*: *V* → *W* its dual *f*∗: *W*∗ → *V*∗.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] The following list of examples shows the common features of many dualities, but also indicates that the precise meaning of duality may vary from case to case.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] A simple duality arises from considering subsets of a fixed set S.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] To any subset *A* ⊆ *S*, the complement *A*∁ (also denoted as *S* \ *A*) consists of all those elements in S that are not contained in A.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] This duality appears in topology as a duality between open and closed subsets of some fixed topological space X: a subset U of X is closed if and only if its complement in X is open.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] Because of this, many theorems about closed sets are dual to theorems about open sets.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] For example, any union of open sets is open, so dually, any intersection of closed sets is closed.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] The interior of a set is the largest open set contained in it, and the closure of the set is the smallest closed set that contains it.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] Because of the duality, the complement of the interior of any set U is equal to the closure of the complement of U.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] A duality in geometry is provided by the dual cone construction.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] Unlike for the complement of sets mentioned above, it is not in general true that applying the dual cone construction twice gives back the original set C .
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] Instead, $C^{**}$ is the smallest cone containing C which may be bigger than C .
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] A very important example of a duality arises in linear algebra by associating to any vector space V its dual vector space *V**.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] Its elements are the linear functionals $\varphi :V\to K$ , where K is the field over which V is defined.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] The three properties of the dual cone carry over to this type of duality by replacing subsets of $\mathbb {R} ^{2}$ by vector space and inclusions of such subsets by linear maps.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] A particular feature of this duality is that V and *V** are isomorphic for certain objects, namely finite-dimensional vector spaces.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] However, this is in a sense a lucky coincidence, for giving such an isomorphism requires a certain choice, for example the choice of a basis of V.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] This is also true in the case if V is a Hilbert space, *via* the Riesz representation theorem.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] In all the dualities discussed before, the dual of an object is of the same kind as the object itself.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] For example, the dual of a vector space is again a vector space.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] Many duality statements are not of this kind.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] Instead, such dualities reveal a close relation between objects of seemingly different nature.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] One example of such a more general duality is from Galois theory.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] For a fixed Galois extension *K* / *F*, one may associate the Galois group Gal(*K*/*E*) to any intermediate field E (i.e., *F* ⊆ *E* ⊆ *K*).
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] This group is a subgroup of the Galois group *G* = Gal(*K*/*F*).
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] Conversely, to any such subgroup *H* ⊆ *G* there is the fixed field *K**H* consisting of elements fixed by the elements in H.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] Given a poset *P* = (*X*, ≤) (short for partially ordered set; i.e., a set that has a notion of ordering but in which two elements cannot necessarily be placed in order relative to each other), the dual poset *P**d* = (*X*, ≥) comprises the same ground set but the converse relation.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] A *duality transform* is an involutive antiautomorphism f of a partially ordered set S, that is, an order-reversing involution *f* : *S* → *S*.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] In several important cases these simple properties determine the transform uniquely up to some simple symmetries.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] For example, if *f*1, *f*2 are two duality transforms then their composition is an order automorphism of S; thus, any two duality transforms differ only by an order automorphism.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] For example, all order automorphisms of a power set *S* = 2*R* are induced by permutations of R.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] A concept defined for a partial order P will correspond to a *dual concept* on the dual poset *P**d*.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] For instance, a minimal element of P will be a maximal element of *P**d*: minimality and maximality are dual concepts in order theory.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] Other pairs of dual concepts are upper and lower bounds, lower sets and upper sets, and ideals and filters.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] In topology, open sets and closed sets are dual concepts: the complement of an open set is closed, and vice versa.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] In matroid theory, the family of sets complementary to the independent sets of a given matroid themselves form another matroid, called the dual matroid.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] There are many distinct but interrelated dualities in which geometric or topological objects correspond to other objects of the same type, but with a reversal of the dimensions of the features of the objects.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] A classical example (known to Euclid) of this is the duality of the Platonic solids, in which the cube and the octahedron form a dual pair, the dodecahedron and the icosahedron form a dual pair, and the tetrahedron is self-dual.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] The dual polyhedron of any of these polyhedra may be formed as the convex hull of the center points of each face of the primal polyhedron, so the vertices of the dual correspond one-for-one with the faces of the primal.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] Similarly, each edge of the dual corresponds to an edge of the primal, and each face of the dual corresponds to a vertex of the primal.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] These correspondences are incidence-preserving: if two parts of the primal polyhedron touch each other, so do the corresponding two parts of the dual polyhedron.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] The incidence-preserving nature of the duality is reflected in the fact that the face lattices of the primal and dual polyhedra or polytopes are themselves order-theoretic duals.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] Duality of polytopes and order-theoretic duality are both involutions: the dual polytope of the dual polytope of any polytope is the original polytope, and reversing all order-relations twice returns to the original order.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] Choosing a different center of polarity leads to geometrically different dual polytopes, but all have the same combinatorial structure.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] From any three-dimensional polyhedron, one can form a planar graph, the graph of its vertices and edges.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] The dual polyhedron has a dual graph, a graph with one vertex for each face of the polyhedron and with one edge for every two adjacent faces.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] An important example of this type comes from computational geometry: the duality for any finite set S of points in the plane between the Delaunay triangulation of S and the Voronoi diagram of S.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] The dual graph depends on how the primal graph is embedded: different planar embeddings of a single graph may lead to different dual graphs.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] Matroid duality is an algebraic extension of planar graph duality, in the sense that the dual matroid of the graphic matroid of a planar graph is isomorphic to the graphic matroid of the dual graph.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] A kind of geometric duality also occurs in optimization theory, but not one that reverses dimensions.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] Every linear program has a dual problem with the same optimal solution, but the variables in the dual problem correspond to constraints in the primal problem and vice versa.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] In logic, functions or relations A and B are considered dual if *A*(¬*x*) = ¬*B*(*x*), where ¬ is logical negation.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] The basic duality of this type is the duality of the ∃ and ∀ quantifiers in classical logic.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] These are dual because ∃*x*.¬*P*(*x*) and ¬∀*x*.*P*(*x*) are equivalent for all predicates *P* in classical logic: if there exists an *x* for which *P* fails to hold, then it is false that *P* holds for all *x* (but the converse does not hold constructively).
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] The dual of the dual, called the **bidual** or **double dual**, depending on context, is often identical to the original (also called *primal*), and duality is an involution.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] In this case the bidual is not usually distinguished, and instead one only refers to the primal and dual.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] For example, the dual poset of a dual poset is exactly the original poset, since the converse relation is defined by an involution.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] In other cases, the bidual is not identical with the primal, though there is often a close connection.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] For example, the dual cone of the dual cone of a set contains the primal set (it is the smallest cone containing the primal set), and is equal if and only if the primal set is a cone.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] An important case is for vector spaces, where there is a map from the primal space to the double dual, *V* → *V***, known as the "canonical evaluation map".
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] For finite-dimensional vector spaces this is an isomorphism, but these are not identical spaces: they are different sets.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] In category theory, this is generalized by § Dual objects, and a "natural transformation" from the identity functor to the double dual functor.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] For vector spaces (considered algebraically), this is always an injection; see Dual space § Injection into the double-dual.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] This can be generalized algebraically to a dual module.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] There is still a canonical evaluation map, but it is not always injective; if it is, this is known as a torsionless module; if it is an isomorphism, the module is called reflexive.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] For topological vector spaces (including normed vector spaces), there is a separate notion of a topological dual, denoted ⁠ $V'$ ⁠ to distinguish from the algebraic dual *V**, with different possible topologies on the dual, each of which defines a different bidual space ⁠ $V''$ ⁠.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] In these cases the canonical evaluation map ⁠ $V\to V''$ ⁠ is not in general an isomorphism.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] If it is, this is known (for certain locally convex vector spaces with the strong dual space topology) as a reflexive space.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] In other cases, showing a relation between the primal and bidual is a significant result, as in Pontryagin duality (a locally compact abelian group is naturally isomorphic to its bidual).
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] A group of dualities can be described by endowing, for any mathematical object X, the set of morphisms Hom (*X*, *D*) into some fixed object D, with a structure similar to that of X.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] In general, this yields a true duality only for specific choices of D, in which case *X** = Hom (*X*, *D*) is referred to as the *dual* of X.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] There is always a map from X to the *bidual*, that is to say, the dual of the dual, $X\to X^{**}:=(X^{*})^{*}=\operatorname {Hom} (\operatorname {Hom} (X,D),D).$ It assigns to some *x* ∈ *X* the map that associates to any map *f* : *X* → *D* (i.e., an element in Hom(*X*, *D*)) the value *f*(*x*).
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] Depending on the concrete duality considered and also depending on the object X, this map may or may not be an isomorphism.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] The construction of the dual vector space $V^{*}=\operatorname {Hom} (V,K)$ mentioned in the introduction is an example of such a duality.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] Indeed, the set of morphisms, i.e., linear maps, forms a vector space in its own right.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] The map *V* → *V*** mentioned above is always injective.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] It is surjective, and therefore an isomorphism, if and only if the dimension of V is finite.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] This fact characterizes finite-dimensional vector spaces without referring to a basis.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] A vector space *V* is isomorphic to *V*∗ precisely if *V* is finite-dimensional.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] In this case, such an isomorphism is equivalent to a non-degenerate bilinear form $\varphi :V\times V\to K$ In this case *V* is called an inner product space.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] For example, if *K* is the field of real or complex numbers, any positive definite bilinear form gives rise to such an isomorphism.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] In Riemannian geometry, *V* is taken to be the tangent space of a manifold and such positive bilinear forms are called Riemannian metrics.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] Their purpose is to measure angles and distances.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] Thus, duality is a foundational basis of this branch of geometry.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] Another application of inner product spaces is the Hodge star which provides a correspondence between the elements of the exterior algebra.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] For an *n*-dimensional vector space, the Hodge star operator maps *k*-forms to (*n* − *k*)-forms.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] This can be used to formulate Maxwell's equations.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] In this guise, the duality inherent in the inner product space exchanges the role of magnetic and electric fields.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] In some projective planes, it is possible to find geometric transformations that map each point of the projective plane to a line, and each line of the projective plane to a point, in an incidence-preserving way.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] For such planes there arises a general principle of duality in projective planes: given any theorem in such a plane projective geometry, exchanging the terms "point" and "line" everywhere results in a new, equally valid theorem.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] A simple example is that the statement "two points determine a unique line, the line passing through these points" has the dual statement that "two lines determine a unique point, the intersection point of these two lines".
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] For further examples, see Dual theorems.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] A conceptual explanation of this phenomenon in some planes (notably field planes) is offered by the dual vector space.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] In fact, the points in the projective plane $\mathbb {RP} ^{2}$ correspond to one-dimensional subvector spaces $V\subset \mathbb {R} ^{3}$ while the lines in the projective plane correspond to subvector spaces W of dimension 2.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] The duality in such projective geometries stems from assigning to a one-dimensional V the subspace of $(\mathbb {R} ^{3})^{*}$ consisting of those linear maps $f:\mathbb {R} ^{3}\to \mathbb {R}$ which satisfy $f(V)=0$ .
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] As a consequence of the dimension formula of linear algebra, this space is two-dimensional, i.e., it corresponds to a line in the projective plane associated to $(\mathbb {R} ^{3})^{*}$ .
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] The (positive definite) bilinear form ${\displaystyle \langle \cdot ,\cdot \rangle$ yields an identification of this projective plane with the $\mathbb {RP} ^{2}$ .
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] Concretely, the duality assigns to $V\subset \mathbb {R} ^{3}$ its orthogonal $\left\{w\in \mathbb {R} ^{3},\langle v,w\rangle =0{\text{ for all }}v\in V\right\}$ .
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] The explicit formulas in duality in projective geometry arise by means of this identification.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] In the realm of topological vector spaces, a similar construction exists, replacing the dual by the topological dual vector space.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] There are several notions of topological dual space, and each of them gives rise to a certain concept of duality.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] The dual lattice of a lattice L is given by $\operatorname {Hom} (L,\mathbb {Z} ),$ the set of linear functions on the real vector space containing the lattice that map the points of the lattice to the integers $\mathbb {Z}$ .
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] This is used in the construction of toric varieties.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] The Pontryagin dual of locally compact topological groups *G* is given by $\operatorname {Hom} (G,S^{1}),$ continuous group homomorphisms with values in the circle (with multiplication of complex numbers as group operation).
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] In another group of dualities, the objects of one theory are translated into objects of another theory and the maps between objects in the first theory are translated into morphisms in the second theory, but with direction reversed.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] That functor may or may not be an equivalence of categories.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] There are various situations, where such a functor is an equivalence between the opposite category *C*op of C, and D.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] Using a duality of this type, every statement in the first theory can be translated into a "dual" statement in the second theory, where the direction of all arrows has to be reversed.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] Therefore, any duality between categories C and D is formally the same as an equivalence between C and *D*op (*C*op and D).
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] However, in many circumstances the opposite categories have no inherent meaning, which makes duality an additional, separate concept.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] A category that is equivalent to its dual is called *self-dual*.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] An example of self-dual category is the category of Hilbert spaces.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] Many category-theoretic notions come in pairs in the sense that they correspond to each other while considering the opposite category.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] Therefore, in some cases, proofs of certain statements can be halved, using such a duality phenomenon.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] Further notions displaying related by such a categorical duality are projective and injective modules in homological algebra, fibrations and cofibrations in topology and more generally model categories.
[src:session-types/duality-mathematics] between the colimit functor that assigns to any diagram in C indexed by some category I its colimit and the diagonal functor that maps any object c of C to the constant diagram which has c at all places.
